Why not just size down on the naked position?

-Defined risk

-Credit spreads profit off of time decay

-Lower BPR
 (more capital to use elsewhere)👇

full_text: Auction Market Theory (AMT) views the market as a continuous auction where price is determined by the ongoing interaction of buyers and sellers, helping traders identify areas of balance (where price is accepted) and imbalance (where price trends).\n\nHere's a simplified breakdown: https://t.co/KnTGfR7EEa
name: Errol Coleman

full_text: When aggressive orders overwhelm passive orders, it is called a liquidity sweep. This occurs when aggressive market orders consume all available passive limit orders (liquidity) at certain price levels, causing price to begin momentum in one direction.\n\nHere's what to look for👇 https://t.co/1CHkOGrjDS
name: Errol Coleman

full_text: A failed auction occurs when the market briefly attempts to break out above or below a key level (like a value area) but quickly reverses, signaling a rejection of the attempted move.\n\nHere's an example of a failed auction👇 https://t.co/uQ3W5SxYHk

full_text:
Ever wonder who’s really in control—buyers or sellers—inside every candlestick? 

That’s where Candlestick Delta on a footprint chart shines.

It’s not just price action; it’s the battle of aggressive orders driving the market. 

Here’s how to read in live market hours: 👇 https://t.co/rrFr1P4DJ6
name: Errol Coleman

full_text:
How delta helps traders:

Confirm trends: Delta matches price direction.

Spot reversals: Weakening delta at key levels.

Catch traps: Bullish candle + negative delta = absorption by sellers.

Mastering delta = trading with real insight.
name: Errol Coleman

full_text:
Misconceptions About Delta ❌ 

1️⃣ High Delta always = strength: 

Not true. Big delta can mean a trap if large players are absorbing orders.

2️⃣ Delta must align with price: 

Divergences happen! Price ↑ but Delta ↓ could mean exhaustion or hidden absorption.
name: Errol Coleman

NASDAQ Market Breakdown – Key Levels to Watch Heading into This Week 

As we head into the upcoming trading week, here’s a breakdown of the NASDAQ market and the 3 key value areas to pay attention to:

📍 Top Value Area

Value Area Low (VAL): 22273
Value Area High (VAH): 22355
Watch for price action around these levels — if price fails to break above this zone, it may signal rejection and potential downside pressure.

📍 Middle Value Area

Value Area Low (VAL): 22092
Value Area High (VAH): 22170
The middle value area is key for understanding potential consolidation or transition zones. If price is ranging between these levels, we could see some sideways movement as the market decides its next direction.

📍 Main Value Area (Most Volume Traded)

Value Area Low (VAL): 21658
Value Area High (VAH): 21878
This is the main value area since it has seen the most volume traded at these levels. The market is in a state of imbalance until proven otherwise, and this value area will act as an important reference for market behavior.

If price remains below the VAL our directional bias will be to the downside
